<DocsLayout title="Getting Started" description="Get started with LeanCTX in under 5 minutes.">
  <p>
    LeanCTX is the <strong>Cognitive Filter</strong> between you and your LLM — a single Rust binary
    that maximizes information density per token. It caches file reads, compresses CLI output with
    90+ patterns, extracts AST-based signatures, and filters low-entropy content.
    The result: sharper reasoning, longer sessions, logarithmic cost.
  </p>

  <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>An MCP-compatible editor: Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Claude Code, Windsurf, OpenAI Codex, Google Antigravity, OpenCode, OpenClaw, or any other MCP-compatible tool</li>
    <li><strong>macOS / Linux:</strong> Homebrew, AUR, or Rust toolchain (<code>cargo install lean-ctx</code>)</li>
    <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Pre-built binary from <a href="https://github.com/yvgude/lean-ctx/releases/latest">GitHub Releases</a> or <code>cargo install lean-ctx</code></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Architecture</h2>
  <p>LeanCTX has two complementary operating modes in a single binary:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Shell Hook</strong> — Wraps CLI commands and compresses output automatically.
        Works without LLM cooperation. 90+ patterns across 34 categories: git, npm, cargo, docker, kubectl, gh, pip, ruff, rubocop, eslint, curl, wget, vitest, terraform, make, maven, dotnet, flutter, poetry, aws, psql, mysql, prisma, helm, bun, deno, swift, zig, cmake, ansible, composer, mix, bazel, systemd, and more.</li>
    <li><strong>MCP Server</strong> — 21 advanced tools for cached reads, dependency maps,
        adaptive mode selection, incremental deltas, intent detection, project graphs, entropy analysis, cache management, benchmarking, and session metrics. Works with any MCP editor.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>
    LeanCTX provides 21 MCP tools that replace or augment your editor's built-in tools. Here are the core tools:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Tool</th>
        <th>Replaces</th>
